<h2>How Does Base64 Encoding Work?</h2>

<p>
  The encoding process takes input in groups of 3 bytes (24 bits) and splits each group into four 6-bit chunks. Each 6-bit chunk maps to one of the 64 characters in the Base64 alphabet:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Values 0–25 → A–Z</li>
  <li>Values 26–51 → a–z</li>
  <li>Values 52–61 → 0–9</li>
  <li>Value 62 → +</li>
  <li>Value 63 → /</li>
</ul>

<p>
  If the input isn't a multiple of 3 bytes, <code>=</code> padding characters are added. One <code>=</code> means one padding byte; <code>==</code> means two.
</p>

<h2>Base64 vs Base64url</h2>

<p>
  Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> as its last two characters. These are problematic in URLs (where <code>+</code> means a space and <code>/</code> is a path separator). <strong>Base64url</strong> replaces them: <code>+</code> → <code>-</code> and <code>/</code> → <code>_</code>. JWT tokens and some APIs use Base64url.
</p>

<h2>How to Encode and Decode Base64 in Code</h2>

<h3>JavaScript (browser or Node.js):</h3>
<p>
  Encode: <code>btoa("Hello, World!")</code> → <code>SGVsbG8sIFdvcmxkIQ==</code><br />
  Decode: <code>atob("SGVsbG8sIFdvcmxkIQ==")</code> → <code>Hello, World!</code>
</p>

<h3>Python:</h3>
<p>
  Encode: <code>import base64; base64.b64encode(b"Hello")</code><br />
  Decode: <code>base64.b64decode("SGVsbG8=")</code>
</p>

<h3>Command line (Linux/Mac):</h3>
<p>
  Encode: <code>echo -n "Hello" | base64</code><br />
  Decode: <code>echo "SGVsbG8=" | base64 --decode</code>
</p>

<h2>Common Base64 Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Using Base64 for security:</strong> Base64 is not encryption. Never encode passwords or sensitive data in Base64 thinking it's protected — it isn't.</li>
  <li><strong>Ignoring the size increase:</strong> Base64 adds ~33% overhead. Avoid Base64-encoding large binary files for storage.</li>
  <li><strong>Forgetting charset for text:</strong> When encoding text strings, specify UTF-8 encoding explicitly to handle non-ASCII characters correctly.</li>
  <li><strong>Confusing Base64 with hex:</strong> Hex (hexadecimal) encoding uses 16 characters (0–9, a–f) and doubles the size. Base64 uses 64 characters and adds ~33%.</li>
</ul>

